What has kept you motivated
and engaged in the organization
for so long?
I was attracted to the foundation's
mission and strategy on Water,
Sanitation, and Hygiene (WASH),
particularly their focus on
sanitation, which I had been
anticipating for a long time. My
primary objective in joining the
foundation was to introduce
innovative sanitation solutions in
the global south, particularly in
South Asia. Prior to joining the
foundation, I wore several hats for
25 years: researcher, academic,
public ocial, activist, and UN ocial. However, none of these roles left
me feeling satised or capable of eecting the necessary changes in the sector.
Today, I am thrilled to say that I have been able to accomplish numerous unnished
missions since joining the foundation. This success is not only attributed to
achieving our mission but is also a testament to the exceptional work environment
we have here, surpassing my imagination when compared to my previous jobs. Even
as a Program Ocer, I have enjoyed complete autonomy in my work, a level of
independence that is rarely found in any other organization. It is something we
should take pride in. If you are an intelligent individual seeking to pursue new and
innovative ideas, this is the only place where we can transform them into reality. In
summary, my motivation to continue working with the foundation with the belief
that every action or step we take has a tangible impact on the ground in a short
period of time. Despite the heavy workload and occasional stress, these challenges
ultimately turn into "Sweet Stress" once we witness the results rsthand.
What lessons have you learned during your journey at Foundation?
I was pleasantly surprised to discover the profound impact philanthropists can have
on society and their ability to create global change. Prior to my recent insights, I
held a limited understanding of their involvement and often assumed that wealthy
individuals must have some hidden agenda behind their contributions, with my
experiences of CSR projects funded by business entities. However, delving deeper
into the subject, I gained a more comprehensive understanding of global
development, particularly in the global south, as well as the functions of
international development organizations and development banks. This new
knowledge has exposed both the strengths and weaknesses of these entities,
illuminating the areas that require optimization of resources. Moreover, I have
learned the importance and ways of empowering local organizations, professionals,
and experts rather than solely relying on international organizations and experts
from the global north. From a professional standpoint, this journey has ignited a
plethora of innovative ideas and management of Shit often considered taboo. It's
refreshing to be able to openly discuss and address this important matter.

If you could give a humorous nickname to your work area or oce,
what would it be and why?
Yeh jagah to Sukhiram or Dukhiram dono milkar kaam karne ka jaga hai! (This place
is like a combination of Sukhiram and Dukhiram working together!)
Some colleagues are exceedingly optimistic and always eager to do more,
symbolizing the spirit of Dukhiram. On the other hand, we have smart individuals
who understand the importance of work-life balance, resembling Sukhiram. I am
currently brainstorming a nickname that blends the qualities of Sukhiram and
Dukhiram, and I will share it in the upcoming "ICO Patrika."

What has kept you motivated and engaged in the organization for so long?
The impact focused mission of the foundation and its ongoing quest to make the world a
better, equitable and healthier place for the underserved. I am extremely grateful to have the
opportunity to work for an organization that allows one to work towards directly, tangibly
and positively impacting peoples lives.
What lessons have you learned during your journey at Foundation?
The four most important lessons I have learnt while at the foundation are:
1. Be patient and optimistic you will get opportunities to learn and contribute
beyond what you had envisioned.
2. Be hands-on and willing to roll up your sleeves.
3. Continue to be passionate about the causes you care for. Remind yourself
regularly why you are here.
4. Do not be risk averse as it inhibits your learning.
If you could sum up your years in the organization in one word,

Maybe I could use two words Purpose and Gratitude.
